doc.after: The Great Crack is an eight-mile-long, 60 feet (18Â m) wide and 60 feet (18Â m) deep fissure in the island, in the district of Kau. According to the United States Geological Survey (USGS), The Great Crack is the result of crustal dilation from magmatic intrusions into the southwest rift zone of Kilauea.[10] While neither the earthquake of 1868 nor that of 1975 caused a measurable change in The Great Crack, lava welled out of the lower 10 kilometers (6.2Â mi) of the Great Crack in 1823.[10]
